text=:Category: TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts%0a:Title: The velar nasal Comparing English and Cantonese%0a:Author: Mingkang_L%0a:Section: A%0a:Completed: 20.02.2021 - 11:26%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210314-185922-518830#%0a* [-14.03.2021 - 11:59-] || TA_audrey marked as complete%0a#foxend 210314-185922-518830#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a#foxbegin 210314-185909-876160#%0a----%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-14.03.2021 - 11:59-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a!!!!!TA_audrey%0a %0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c%0a{[foxdelrange button 210314-185909-876160 {$FullName} ]}%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1end:)%0a#foxend 210314-185909-876160#%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aThere is no initial velar nasal in English but there is in Cantonese... but the full picture is more complex.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThe velar nasal: Comparing English and Cantonese%0aThe velar nasal [ŋ] exists in both English and Cantonese, but WALS shows that English has no initial velar nasal [ŋ]. It can appear in the coda such as in the word “ring,” “wrinkle,” but not in the onset. However, the velar nasal in Cantonese can appear both in simple onset (e.g. 我 “I” is pronounced as [ŋɔ̃] or [ŋɔ]) and in the coda of a syllable (e.g. 星 “star” [seŋ]), and it can also be a syllable by itself (五 “five” [ŋ̩]). Since Cantonese doesn’t have consonant clusters, the velar nasal can’t be combined with other consonants in the onset. %0aHowever, the initial velar nasal is being dropped and merged into the null initial by younger speakers of Cantonese. Words with initial velar nasals such as 我”I” [ŋɔ̃], 牙”tooth”[ŋa], 眼”eye” [ŋan], “爱“ [ŋɔɪ], etc., are pronounced as [ɔ], [a], [an], and [ɔɪ] , respectively. The syllabic [ŋ] is also being replaced by [m] in words such as 五“five” and 唔”negation.” The phenomenon of dropping the initial velar nasals is referred to as 懒音, or “lazy sound” translated word for word. Although initial velar nasals do exist in standard Cantonese, it is usually dropped among the younger generations and doesn’t serve a contrastive function anymore, much similar to what has happened to the initial velar nasal in Mandarin a few centuries ago. The reason why Cantonese dropped the initial velar nasal might be that it takes some effort to produce, even for native speakers. Did similar things happen in other languages. From a broader perspective, is it a natural tendency for languages to drop the initial [ŋ], or more generally, is it natural for languages to drop the phonemes which are harder to produce?%0a%0aSource:%0ahttps://wals.info/feature/9A#2/51.0/151.9%0aTo, Carol K. S.; Mcleod, Sharynne; Cheung, Pamela S. P. (2015). "Phonetic variations and sound changes in Hong Kong Cantonese: diachronic review, synchronic study and implications for speech sound assessment". Clinical Linguistics & Phonetics. 29 (5): 333–353.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_audrey:)
