standard Cantonese, it is usually dropped among the younger generations and doesn’t serve a contrastive function anymore, much similar to what has happened to the initial velar nasal in Mandarin a few centuries ago. The reason why Cantonese dropped the initial velar nasal might be that it takes some effort to produce, even for native speakers. Did similar things happen in other languages. From a broader perspective, is it a natural tendency for languages to drop the initial [ŋ], or more generally, is it natural for languages to drop the phonemes which are harder to produce?%0a%3c %0a%3c Source:%0a%3c https://wals.info/feature/9A#2/51.0/151.9%0a%3c To, Carol K. S.; Mcleod, Sharynne; Cheung, Pamela S. P. (2015). "Phonetic variations and sound changes in Hong Kong Cantonese: diachronic review, synchronic study and implications for speech sound assessment". Clinical Linguistics & Phonetics. 29 (5): 333–353.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
